  "prompt": "What are typical revenue sharing models for 3rd party vendors for enterprise software companies?",
  "response": "Here are some common revenue sharing models for 3rd party vendors in enterprise software:\n\n1. Percentage-Based Models\n- Percentage of total software sale (10-30%)\n- Percentage of recurring subscription revenue\n- Tiered percentages based on sales volume\n\n2. Referral Commission Models\n- Flat fee per successful sale\n- Percentage commission on initial sale\n- Ongoing commission for customer retention\n\n3. Licensing Models\n- Per-user licensing fees\n- Usage-based licensing\n- Perpetual vs. annual licensing fees\n- Royalty payments based on total software usage\n\n4. Marketplace/Ecosystem Models\n- Fixed platform listing fees\n- Transaction-based revenue share\n- Tiered commission structures\n\n5. Professional Services Models\n- Hourly consulting rates\n- Project-based revenue sharing\n- Implementation service fees\n\n6. Co-selling/Strategic Partnership Models\n- Joint marketing investment\n- Shared sales pipeline\n- Mutually negotiated revenue splits\n\n7. Integration/Add-on Models\n- Fixed integration fees\n- Percentage of associated revenue\n- Bundled pricing structures\n\nSpecific percentages and structures vary widely based on:\n- Software category\n- Vendor relationship\n- Target market\n- Complexity of integration\n- Strategic importance of partnership\n\nEach model has unique advantages depending on business objectives and partnership dynamics.",
